d Stephen Hawking, and it has published many of the most important discoveries in the history of science, including articles on the structure of DNA, the discovery of the neutron, the first cloning of a mammal, and the human genome. But how did Nature become such an essential institution? In Making "Nature," Melinda Baldwin charts the rich history of this extraordinary publication from its foundation in 1869 to current debates about online publishing and open access. This pioneering study not only tells Nature's story but also sheds light on much larger questions about the history of science publishing, changes in scientific communication, and shifting notions of "scientific community." Nature, as Baldwin demonstrates, helped define what science is and what it means to be a scientist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aScience publishingxHistory. 0aSciencexPeriodicalsxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ascience, scientific, journals, academic, scholarly, publications, nature, magazine, publishing, contributors, scientists, charles darwin, ernest rutherford, stephen hawking, discoveries, articles, reading, dna, genome, cloning, technology, advancement, study, professor, learning, community, consensus, questions, research, hypothesis, data, textbook, college, university, 1800s, 1900s, 20th century, contemporary, modern, self policing, global, international.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022626145440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226261591423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226261591/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles